We're over on Broadmoor, and I have the pleasure of interviewing Ned Walton, class of?
Ned, to introduce yourself to anyone that might hear the tape or read a transcription, give a biographical summary of,
your background and family and where you grew up, went to high school and so forth, before you came to A&M.
High school I was raised up in what's called the Arklatex area, about halfway between Texarkana and Shreveport, right on the state line, a little place called Walton Center.
It actually was the state line.
Our farm bordered the state line.
and one of six children.
Three boys, three girls.
There was actually four boys.
One boy died as an infant a couple weeks old with pneumonia, whooping cough, something of that sort back in the old days.
Hard to treat in those days.
But I was raised there in the architects.
We had a history there in the family.
My dad worked for an oil company.
He was an oil field pumper and gauger.
The old Standard Oil of Indiana brand, Amoco, and some of those companies are part of that family.
The oil field up in that area consisted of the McLeod oil field, the Rhodessa oil field, and the Oil City area.
And all of that was just on the edge of that big East Texas oil field.
So I was raised in
that part of the world, and some people call that still in the oil patch.
Very well brought up by my parents to appreciate everything in life, to appreciate education.
My dad was very insistent that the kids get education, and he said there will always be a way for you to go to school.
I went to McLeod.
McLeod was 12 grades all on one campus, separated between the first six grades and the second six grades by the cafeteria and the auditorium.
How many in your senior grade?
I had about 20 or 21 in my senior class, which was a very, very large class for McLeod.
It was a little class B school back in those days, and there were...
I believe maybe five boys in that class, and the rest were girls.
Or maybe I have that reversed.
I don't even remember now.
But there were not a lot of us, and I had a real interesting thing to happen to me when I was in high school that really prepared me and let me come to A&M.
I had done well in high school as a student, but the course offerings were rather limited.
There was a young man that graduated from East Texas State and went up to the University of Oklahoma and got degrees in math and physics.
He was a high school classmate at McLeod of one of my older sisters.
The boy's name was Ross Evans.
Ross was hired by NASA.
before NASA existed.
He received his master's at, like I said, OU in math and physics.
And they had a job for him at Huntsville, Alabama, whenever Huntsville got up and running.
And there was a one-year lag in between the time he graduated from OU and starting his NASA job.
And he came to McLeod High School and taught.
And in my senior year, he taught me physics,
trigonometry, solid geometry, and I guess what we'd call precalculus.
And he said, if you're going to go to one of the major schools, an A&M or Texas or whatever, you really need this preparation.
And probably had it not been for that, I'd have a much tougher time at A&M than what I did.
But that's where I came from.
It's a little bit of my background.
My mother was from Arkansas.
My father

His ancestors settled a little place of Walton Center there on the state line, and actually not only there in Walton Center, but in Caddo Parish, Louisiana, Miller County, Arkansas, Cass County, Texas.
That was pretty much the centroid area of where the Waltons landed, and still have the farm there in Walton Center, and one of my sisters lives there on the farm.
Did you come to visit A&M before you came to enroll?
I had been to A&M one time.
Now, my brother, my oldest brother, 12 years my senior, spent two years at what was called Magnolia A&M.
I guess that was in...
trying to think what Arkansas, I guess it's maybe Arkansas State now.
Anyway, at Magnolia A&M, a little place in Magnolia, Arkansas, and transferred to A&M and spent three years at A&M and took a petroleum engineering degree, class of 51.
And so I had a chance when I was a very small child to come down one time and had no impression whatsoever of being here.
But my brother put me in Aggie T-shirts and that sort of thing when I was a kid.
And I can remember some photographs of wearing the Aggie T-shirt that my brother had brought to me.
But that was my only real connection direct with A&M when I was a youngster.
Now, we had a lot of history.
both in the Walton family and in McCloud that was A&M related.
And so I had a real strong push, if you will, to consider A&M.
So you came to A&M largely for impersonal reasons, by that I mean without any direct contact.
Did some teachers encourage you?
Yes, my high school principal was an Aggie, Lewis Hamm.
Went on to become superintendent at McLeod, and then superintendent at Como-Picton, also over in East Texas.
And my brother, an Aggie, I had several cousins that were Aggies.
The three McLeod boys, Max, Curtis, and Gerald, were all A&M graduates by that time.
James Odom, who was two classes ahead of me, and Jim Stewart, three classes ahead of me, McLeod graduates all came to A&M.
In fact, Jim Stewart was a civil engineering graduate, and I
he probably had a little bit of influence going into the civil area.
I really started in math and physics because of this high school teacher, Ross Evans, who was going to NASA.

I really enjoyed the math and physics that I got as a senior, so I went from math and physics to civil engineering, back to math and physics, and back to civil engineering, all in my freshman year, and finally settled on civil engineering.
So maybe it was impersonal reasons that I came to A&M, but there was a long
history of some McLeod folks coming to A&M and then relatives coming to A&M.
Now, you come down to enroll in the fall of 58 or 59?
I actually came to summer school for six weeks.
Describe that.
Very interesting.
Really, it was my brother's recommendation.
He said, little brother,
You're going to get down there in that forest of trees, and you're not going to know where you are or what you're doing, and it's going to be very traumatic for you coming out of McLeod.
I know it was traumatic for me going from Magnolia A&M down there to spend a few years.
So I think it would be good for you to go down there in summer school.
So I worked half that summer and came down for the second session of summer school.
and took college algebra and college trig, I guess it was, and that's six weeks of summer school.
You lived on campus.
Lived on campus.
Let me think.
Haskell, I believe in that summer I lived in what they would call Mitchell Hall.
I believe it was Mitchell Hall.
And I remember very much the Grove, Guyon Hall, things from that summer.
It was a very fast six weeks.
Oh, it was extremely fast.
And you did okay academically?
Well, I would say we did okay.
I think I made a couple of B's maybe in those classes.
And then you go home.
Go home.
What did you tell your folks your impression was?
I told them it was a go.
I really enjoyed it, and I was looking forward to going back for the fall semester, being in the Corps.
And at that point, your major was going to be what?
Math and physics.
And what did you think that was going to lead to?
I had no earthly idea, Haskell.
It was a matter of...
of Ross really encouraging me in the math and physics area.
By the way, I saw him Thanksgiving.
I told him that whether he knows it or not, he was a large part of my life
in the years ahead.
This is your older brother?
No, this is the guy that taught the math and physics to me in high school.
Oh, how good.
Yes, I just, you know, that really meant something to me that you probably don't know, but probably had I not had that experience, I would have had a real difficult time in engineering at A&M.
But I had no idea where math and physics, well, maybe it would lead me to NASA or somewhere like that, high school, but...
Now, you go home then, and as you come back to enroll, how did you get down here?
My daddy put me in a 55 model Studebaker.
Wow.
That was the first new car my dad ever bought, was a 55 Studebaker.
Little 600 Champion.
And he had put me in a little 50-mile Studebaker when I was in high school.
So he passed that?
When I say he put me in it, we worked together and we bought that little Studebaker.
But he passed down...
a 55 Studebaker Champion to me when I came to A&M.
And he bought him a little 59 model Lark Studebaker, a little station wagon.
Something behind that one, too, because when my dad died, I inherited that vehicle to finish up school.
But he put me that little 55 Studebaker, and I drove to A&M in that little 55 Studebaker.
As you can remember, what stuff did you bring home?
in that car to become a freshman?
Not much.
A footlocker, which they had told us we had to have.
One blanket, a couple of changes of bedding, towels, washcloths, that sort of thing.
Very, very nominal shoes and socks and underwear and pants and that sort of stuff.
Very, very minimum.
No furniture, no rugs, nothing like that.
It was essentially a foot locker and a couple of sacks full of them.
Did you know before you got down here on that trip, did you know what outfit you were going to be in?
Haskell, I don't believe I did.
I believe that when we got down and started the enrollment process, of course the enrollment process was different then than what I experienced as a prof there, but
I was assigned to an engineering company.
And it was real interesting because the engineering company, all of the freshmen essentially that went into that outfit, and that was H-1 became G-2 after a year or so.
H-1 was disbanded.
All of the freshmen, essentially in that outfit, were engineers, but very few of the upperclassmen were engineers.
They had already gone off to business and agriculture, some of the other majors.
Engineering seemed to be a real tough washout in those days.
What kind of advice...
an instruction did a new fish get in that outfit?

Oh, goodness, Haskell, that there would be call to quarters and that it would be monitored very rigorously and that you were expected to be at four-point stance at your desk during all call to quarters, which
which meant arms and elbows on the chair arms and feet on the floor.
During call to quarters, you couldn't prop your feet up, couldn't lean back in your chair.
You had to be right at that desk.
Academics really seemed to be real prime to the first sergeant, a boy named Charlie Rollins, and to the CO.
They really said, you know, you're really going to have to work hard to
make it academically because not many of you are going to make it through your freshman year.
Not many of us did as a matter of fact.
And you were in what dorm?
We were in dorm 14.
That was called the old dorm area.
The new dorm area was dorm 2 through 12 over on the other side of campus.
But that was the old dorm area and dorm 14 was the guard room.
a dorm located on the bottom floor.
I guess that would be roughly the north end of that dorm.
We were in dorm 14.
And you get a roommate or so.
Yes.
Describe that roommate and that room and how y'all worked it out.
That roommate was a boy named Bill Burnett.
Bill had two brothers, Duke Burnett and Don Burnett, who were upperclassmen at the time.
One was a sophomore and junior.
The other was a senior at A&M at the time.
Bill came in as a freshman.
It was from Terrell, a friend of one Jim Keller.
from Terrell, who was on the football team as a freshman, and of course later coached some at A&M.
But Bill was my official lady.
Bill was no better prepared for the shock of the coronation than I was, even though he came from a larger place.
It was just, you know, for the first few weeks, it was just trauma one day after the other.
You didn't know what to expect or what was coming up next.
What did the upperclassmen tell you all to do and not to do?
told us all those things that you had to do like whipping out and how you were to eat in the mess hall at Sabisa and things, other things not to do.
Be real careful around the bulls.
Make sure that you learned how to address them and salute them real quick and
All those were the proper dos and what have you.
And the don'ts were don't mess with upperclassmen.
Leave them alone and no water drown outs, you know, no babble bombs, that sort of thing in the dorms.
But be prepared for the first water fight.
be prepared for the first male fight in Sebesa, that they would come.
That was just part of old Army bull.
And we were, I will tell you, we were taught and told what to expect.
Did they give you any advice about going to class and studying and taking notes?
Well, they did.
In each of the outfits, there was a scholastic officer, if you will, and a scholastic sergeant.
And then there was somebody assigned to make sure that all of the freshmen were at their desk during call to quarters.
And they monitored our attendance and monitored our grades.
They would ask on a weekly basis how we were doing.
And had, you know, the scholastic sergeant, best I remember, had the old poop file.
You know, there was a room in the core dorm, and I guess every company had it, where literally there were just dozens of files of old quizzes from every prof on campus.
And so they kind of taught you a little bit how to old poop it.
And that seemed to be part of the process.
Did you and other fish go down and look at those files?
Oh, goodness, yes.
Oh, yes.
And it was very disheartening to go into a file and not be able to find anything on a particular prof, especially one that you were really afraid of, a prof that was really.
Do you remember any of the courses that first semester?
Yes.
And that's what I'm going to tell you about one.
And this can certainly go into the record.
You taught me History 105 as a first semester freshman.

and why i remember that so well is that you went through the total roster asking every freshman where was hometown and when i told you hometown was mcleod you said oh yes that's up in northeast texas just on the state line across from louisiana and i was tremendously impressed with that and still don't know till today haskell and perhaps someday you'll confess to me
You either knew your history extremely well and geography better, or you had reviewed that roster and had gone to the map and tried to find where all these students were from.
And it was just absolutely delightful for me to know that you knew where I kind of started saying, oh my goodness,
There's hope.
People know where McLeod is.
As far as I know, it was just having had that trivia memory of where the towns are.
That was fall of 59, and you were, I don't know if you were fish or not yourself, you were a first year or very close to just arriving at A&M.
That was my first year.
I had come from Rice.
I had a temporary nine-month job that lasted 21 years.
How interesting.
I was filling in for a guy that was on leave,
And in the middle of the year, he said he wouldn't come back, and so Dr. Nance told me I could stay.
Well, I'll be... Yeah, I remember that.
Some other first semester.
I certainly remember the courses.
I remember that first English class, and...
how disheartening two or three D's and F's in a row were on the first papers of what they were requiring.
It was so different from what we had seen in high school, but got with the program fairly soon.
And I was not just a real outstanding freshman student.
As far as that goes, I don't guess I was an outstanding student in undergraduate school at all.
I got through and was not ashamed of it.
Got me into graduate school and through a Ph.D. program.
But you didn't make any low grades that first semester, did you?
I don't believe I made a D. I think everything was C or better that first semester.
And you were taking about how many hours?
Oh, goodness, Haskell.
Back then, see, a civil engineering degree was 160 hours.
So we were, and six of that was in summer school between your junior and senior year, which was the surveying camp out at Junction, which I remember very well, too.
But we were taking 19 or 20 hours every semester.
You had to.
And by the way, I graduated in eight semesters plus two summers.
I laid out
one semester, first semester of my sophomore year.
I lost my father.
And I laid out a semester to kind of get things together and find money to come back to school.
And that's where I developed a very strong banking relationship with folks in Bryan College Station to help me go to school.
It scared me to this day, as a matter of fact.
I developed friendships back then that still exist.
But I was 18, 19, probably at least as an average.
I don't know of any semesters that I had the luxury of 12, 14, 15.
I don't remember anything like that.
Describe as much as you can your typical life.
weekday routine during that freshman year?
What time did you get up and what did you do when?
Gosh, it was, in retrospect, I can look back and say it wasn't all that bad, but at the time it was absolutely horrible.
It was getting up at whistle jock, blowing the whistle at I guess 6.15, 6.30 in the morning.
You're getting up in the shower and shaving, cleaning up, getting your uniform on, preparing your room for inspection, which was going to happen sometime whether you wanted it to or not.
And going to chow and just

putting it down as fast as you could feed it in your mouth because of time constraint, getting back to the room and being sure that you had a quarter flippin' off of your bed top, you know, tightly pulled together, military corners and everything, and knowing some upperclassmen gonna come back by and take a look, probably even before class, and harass you, kind of delay you time-wise, and then trying to rush to that first class.
pretty much in class.
There was not a lot of free time during the day.
You were in class, it seems like, much more than they are now.
You know, if you were taking 18, 19 hours with a couple of laboratories, you know, you add another six hours.
You were literally in class 25, 26 hours a week.
And engineering graphics was even worse than that.
That was a two-hour credit class.
I think we were spending maybe eight hours in the classroom on engineering graphics, so it was real heavy, real heavy in the classroom.
If you had any free time during the day,
Where did you spend that time?
Well, you know, you would want to go back to your room, but goodness, the upperclassmen, I mean, that was, you were asking for it if you went back to your room.
Now, that was punishment.
The upperclassmen see you come down the hall, Fish Walton, what are you doing, and where are you going?
And they would occupy your time for you.
So we found other places to go.
We'd go to the Student Center, MSC.
We would hang out there.
Couldn't go off campus, obviously.
I mean, a freshman had no right to go off campus for any reason at any time.
Maybe venture a little bit off campus on Sunday to go to church.
That was about it.
You didn't go off on weekends and what have you until it was announced usually at Saturday drill.
a free afternoon, which meant that you could go out on Saturday night and go to the campus theater or even go downtown to the palace or somewhere if you felt like you wanted to, but a busy, busy day.
That freshman year, did you find any place where you could go slip off and take a nap?
like in the library?
Haskell, yes, I did in fact go to the library and sneak naps because you weren't sleeping well at night.
At the time, you know, have a few wake-ups in the middle of the night to run a few times around campus or go into the shower and have a
you know, one of the sessions in the shower, the upperclassmen's, where they turn on all the hot water and see how long you last, you know, that sort of thing.
So, yeah, a library was a frequent place to go to.
Well, not only, and I will admit to you, I even used the library for academic purposes, but yes, I've been known to sneaking up at the library.
Now, when y'all, in the dorm you were in, when y'all fell out to march to chow, where did you
Y'all fell out right in front of the dorm?
Right in that quadrangle that was between 14, 15, and 16.
They formed a U there in that quad, and we fell out in that quad area.
It was a flagpole right at the end of the quad, and we marched right straight up to Sabisa.
How often did y'all go over to the core area, the new core area?
toward Duncan and participate in anything over there?
The only time we essentially got together like that was on Saturdays.
We'd all go to the drill field on Saturdays or some other place where we had, and we had Saturday drills every Saturday.
I don't remember not having drills on Saturday for my total core experience.
And that was either on the drill field or somewhere else.

we would uh... see we got moved see I laid out that first semester of my sophomore year and I came back in to the core really beginning of my junior year and we had moved over to what's called the new dorm area uh... H-1 had been disbanded and we became G-2
And so then we were located.
Then we were in dorm two, which was the core dorm, where headquarters was located, and ended up in dorm two.
And so, of course, all of our fallouts and everything was in that big quadrangle there.
Now, and I should have asked earlier, there was no fish camp.
No, no fish camp.
And did they give you all any advice on how to study, how to prepare?
Did anybody?
Haskell, very minimal, if anything.
Again,
even most of the upperclassmen were not engineers.
They'd already gone to marketing and business and what have you.
And they told us about call to quarters.
Maybe there was a little bit, they did encourage us
to go to the library, spend as much time in the library as we could, use the old quiz files and what have you as much as we could.
If there were such things as review sessions, we'd go to review sessions.
But those were extremely limited in those days.
And we had to sign out, of course, to go to places like that.
If you left CQ and called quarters and said, I'm going to the library, upperclassmen had to sign your, and you put that on your door.
You go to the library, you better be in the library.
And then they checked up on you every once in a while.
That fish year, did you and your buddies attempt any goofy stuff in the chow hall?
Yeah.
Any tricks, pranks?
Well, yeah.
We were involved in, you know.
Such as?
Accidentally flipping a whole bowl full of stewed tomatoes and boiled okra off on an upperclassman.
Be clumsy and feign it, and then pay the penalty for it.
We could not start food fights.
That was left to the upperclassmen.
But we participated.
I can remember putting the old big rolls in the water pitchers and splattering those all over.
Many, many times I was a good hog caller.
And the week of Arkansas game, freshmen had to stand up in their chair at the chow hall and call the hogs.
And I was a pretty good hog caller, being an old farm boy, so I got to do that a lot.
Got to poke fun at Rice and SMU and some of the other schools during those weeks.
Do you remember what it was like to go to those first football games as a fish?
Yeah, it was, you were lucky if you could have the opportunity to have a date to go, you know.
Most all those football games were, we marched in, and most of us, most fish without dates.
I mean, we were far, far from home, and it was hard to get a girl in.
So what did you and your buddies do then after the game was over?
Oh, Haskell, goodness.
You know, other than chasing down the Yale leaders and participating in that kind of revelry, I don't recall a lot of things real exciting happening after the ball games.
Did, at that point, that freshman year, did you have some spending money?
Did you have a kind of a budget?
Very, very limited.
had you earned it, or had your parents given it to you, or some of both?
It was a little bit of both.
My dad, again, was very insistent that I was going to school, was very pleased that I was going to A&M because big brother had graduated from A&M.
He was very much against my oldest brother coming to A&M.
He wanted my oldest brother to be a school teacher and did not need to go all the way down to College Station to get a
